			<p>In his national forecast released today, a University of Central Florida economist says the White House is suffering from an &ldquo;audacity of scope.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
Sean Snaith says President Obama should first focus on completing the rollout of massive stimulus funding -- something that many economists and officials say is slowly stabilizing the economy -- before tackling health care reform and cap-and-trade policies. <br />
<br />
&ldquo;The administration is trying to attack multiple problems simultaneously, and in doing so, isn&rsquo;t adequately addressing any of them,&rdquo; said Snaith, the director of UCF&rsquo;s Institute for Economic Competitiveness. &ldquo;Successfully solving any one of these would be the crown jewel of the administration. What we&rsquo;re getting now is &lsquo;cubic zirconia&rsquo; policy.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
The recession is nearly over, but it doesn&rsquo;t feel like it, Snaith said. Last week&rsquo;s unemployment figures were still at record levels, and the national debt continues to grow.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;The policies laid out during the campaign are not meeting the cold calculus of budgetary finance,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Hope and change lay defeated at the feet of scarcity.&rdquo; <br />
<br />
Snaith&rsquo;s full third-quarter U.S. forecast is available at <a href="http://www.iec.ucf.edu">www.iec.ucf.edu</a>.<br />
<br />
Highlights of his report also include:<br />
<br />
-- Snaith&rsquo;s earlier &ldquo;gravy boat-shaped recession&rdquo; has been redubbed the &ldquo;genie&rsquo;s lamp recession&rdquo; &ndash; not because the forecasted shape of recovery has changed, but because we&rsquo;ll all be wishing for stronger job growth during the next year.<br />
<br />
-- After at least 18 months of the worst recession since the Great Depression, signs of recovery are multiplying. The recovery will start in the third quarter of 2009, but growth will remain weak during the first five quarters of this expansion.<br />
<br />
-- The nation will have shed 7.6 million payroll jobs before the employment drain hole is plugged after the first quarter of 2010.<br />
<br />
-- Housing starts have finally hit bottom. Starts will slowly rise from this historic low but will remain below one million annually through 2010. <br />
<br />
-- Oil prices, which precipitously fell after spiking to record highs last summer, have already climbed in anticipation of the recovery. Prices will continue to climb to the low $90s per barrel by the end of 2013.<br />
<br />
Snaith is a national expert in economics, forecasting, market sizing and economic analysis who authors quarterly reports about the state of the economy. Bloomberg News recently named Snaith as one of the country&rsquo;s most accurate forecasters for his predictions about the Federal Reserve's benchmark interest rate, the Federal Funds rate. <br />
<br />
Snaith is also a member of several national forecasting panels, including the Western Blue Chip Economic Forecast panel, the National Association of Business Economics Quarterly Outlook Survey Panel, the Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia's Survey of Professional Forecasters, Bloomberg U.S. Economic Indicator Survey and USA Today Economic Survey Panel. Blue Chip named him the most accurate forecaster for California in 2007.<br />
<br />
The UCF Institute for Economic Competitiveness' mission is to expand public understanding of the economy by convening business leaders, scholars, policy makers, civic groups and media to discuss critical issues.<br />
<br />
Snaith is also the host of &quot;Money Talk$ America,&quot; a show produced by UCF TV, which aims to break down complex issues into digestible news about subjects as diverse as interest rates, the job market and the cost of food.<br />
<br />
Watch episodes at <a href="http://www.ucftv.ucf.edu/shows/money_talks/">http://www.ucftv.ucf.edu/shows/money_talks/</a>.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity: </strong>The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 5th largest in the nation with more than 52,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
